        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local Visibility Score</strong> is a composite metric measuring how prominently a business appears in local search results. It aggregates Local Pack positions across multiple keywords, geographic coverage from geo grid rank tracking, and local organic rankings into a single number — making it possible to track overall local search presence over time and compare it against competitors.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Result timeline</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-6 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Tracking cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Monthly</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Individual rank position tracking answers "where do I rank for keyword X?" Local Visibility Score answers a different, more useful question: "how visible am I across all the ways customers search for my category, in all the areas I serve?" That second question is what actually drives revenue.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Local Visibility Score?</h2>
        <p>Local Visibility Score is not a single Google metric — it is a concept implemented differently across local SEO tools. The underlying logic is consistent: combine multiple indicators of local search presence into one normalized score that can be tracked over time and compared against competitors.</p>
        <p>Depending on the tool calculating it, a Local Visibility Score typically aggregates:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Local Pack coverage:</strong> What percentage of tracked keywords return the business in the Local Pack top 3? Top 7?</li>
          <li><strong>Average Local Pack position:</strong> Across all tracked keywords, what is the mean ranking position?</li>
          <li><strong>Geographic spread:</strong> Using geo grid data, what percentage of the service area shows green (positions 1-3) vs. yellow vs. red?</li>
          <li><strong>Local organic visibility:</strong> For queries that generate local organic results, where does the business appear?</li>
          <li><strong>GBP impression share:</strong> What percentage of available impressions is the business capturing via GBP?</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Tools like BrightLocal, Local Falcon, and Semrush each produce visibility scores using weighted combinations of these signals. The exact weighting differs, so scores from different tools are not directly comparable — but trends within a single tool over time are the real value.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Score vs. rank</div>
          <p>A single keyword rank tells you "position 3 for plumber Denver." A Local Visibility Score tells you "83 out of 100 — you're in top 3 for 7 of your 10 tracked keywords, and your geo grid shows green across 68% of your service area." That composite picture is what correlates with lead volume, not any individual ranking.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Local Visibility Score matters</h2>
        <p>Five reasons to track Local Visibility Score alongside individual keyword rankings:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Single KPI for local SEO health.</strong> Local SEO involves dozens of signals across multiple platforms. A single score that aggregates them lets you monitor overall health without reviewing 20 different data points monthly.</li>
          <li><strong>Detects compound problems early.</strong> A business can hold position 1 for its primary keyword while losing visibility across 8 secondary keywords. Individual rank tracking misses the compound erosion; a visibility score catches it because it weights breadth, not just peak position.</li>
          <li><strong>Enables direct competitor comparison.</strong> Run the same visibility score calculation for your top 2-3 competitors. The gap between your score and theirs shows how much room for growth exists — and whether your local SEO investment is closing or widening that gap.</li>
          <li><strong>Connects local SEO effort to business outcomes.</strong> Visibility score improvements correlate with lead volume increases. A business that moved from 45 to 78 on Local Falcon's visibility score saw a 60% increase in GBP impressions — a number a client or stakeholder can connect to the business impact.</li>
          <li><strong>Geographic strategy input.</strong> Visibility scores broken down by neighborhood or service area zone show where to concentrate content and link-building effort for maximum score improvement per unit of work.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Local Visibility Score is calculated</h2>
        <p>Most tools use a variation of this framework:</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Simplified Local Visibility Score formula</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Pack coverage</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">% of keywords in top-3 x weight</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Avg position</span>  <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">Inverse ranking score x weight</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Geo spread</span>    <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">% green grid squares x weight</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Organic local</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> <span class="uf-new">Page 1 local organic visibility x weight</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-status">Composite score: 0-100 (or tool-specific scale)</span>
        </div>

        <p>In practice, a business with strong geo grid coverage but weak keyword depth scores differently from one with top rankings for 3 keywords but limited geographic reach. The score forces a holistic assessment rather than optimizing one signal in isolation.</p>

        <h2 id="examples">Local Visibility Score in practice</h2>

        <h3>1. Denver plumber — from invisible to visible</h3>
        <p>A Denver plumbing company had an initial Local Visibility Score of 22 (BrightLocal scale). The score reflected: Local Pack top-3 coverage on 2 of 10 tracked keywords, average pack position of 6.4, and a geo grid showing 18% green coverage. After 6 months of local SEO — GBP optimization, citation cleanup, 20 new reviews, 4 neighborhood landing pages — the score reached 67. The 60% improvement in GBP impressions tracked directly with the score movement. The business averaged 3-5 inbound calls from Google weekly, versus near-zero before.</p>

        <h3>2. Restaurant chain — cross-location benchmarking</h3>
        <p>A 12-location restaurant group used Local Visibility Score to benchmark performance across locations. Four locations had scores in the 30-40 range while the other eight clustered between 60-80. Analysis showed the underperforming locations had inconsistent NAP data from a previous address change. After citation correction and a GBP photo refresh for those 4 locations, scores rose to 65-75, with a corresponding 60% improvement in GBP impressions in the first quarter.</p>

        <h3>3. Hair salon — competitive benchmarking</h3>
        <p>A new salon owner tracked her Local Visibility Score (44) against her primary competitor (78). The 34-point gap quantified what the business could see anecdotally: the competitor appeared for almost every "hair salon near me" variation, while the owner's salon showed up inconsistently. The gap made the case for sustained local SEO investment more clearly than any keyword report could.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local Visibility Score vs. individual rank tracking</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
