            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for improving Local Visibility Score</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Establish a baseline before any optimization.</strong> Record your score (and competitors' scores) on day 1. Without a pre-campaign benchmark, you cannot demonstrate that your efforts moved the number. Export the baseline data from whatever tool you use and store it permanently.</li>
          <li><strong>Track 10-15 keywords, not just 1-3.</strong> Local Visibility Score is only as good as the keyword breadth it covers. Include your primary service keywords, secondary service terms, and 2-3 "near me" variants. A score based on 3 keywords misses 80% of how customers actually search.</li>
          <li><strong>Run a competitor visibility benchmark monthly.</strong> Your score improving from 45 to 60 looks good until you see your primary competitor moved from 50 to 75 in the same period. Absolute improvement matters less than relative improvement against competitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Focus improvement efforts on review velocity and GBP freshness first.</strong> These two factors have the fastest and most reliable impact on Local Visibility Score because they directly affect prominence — Google's most dynamic local ranking signal. Review volume and recency respond to systematic outreach within 30-60 days.</li>
          <li><strong>Use score breakdowns to prioritize geographic investment.</strong> If your tool shows the score broken down by neighborhood zone, the lowest-scoring areas within your service radius are the highest-ROI content and link targets. Address those red zones with neighborhood landing pages and locally-cited content before chasing new service areas.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — tracking score without context</div>
          <p>A Local Visibility Score of 65 means nothing without knowing what the top competitor scores, what you scored 6 months ago, and what keywords the score is based on. Always track your score alongside at least one competitor, always compare to your own historical baseline, and always know which keywords feed the calculation. A rising score on weak keywords can mask falling visibility on high-value ones.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Local Visibility Score mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Tracking too few keywords</strong> — A score based on 3 keywords doesn't represent your actual local search presence. Include all meaningful service and location keyword combinations.</li>
          <li><strong>Not benchmarking competitors</strong> — Your absolute score tells you little without knowing whether you're gaining or losing ground relative to the businesses competing for the same customers.</li>
          <li><strong>Confusing tool scores</strong> — Different tools produce different numbers for the same business because they weight signals differently. Pick one tool and track consistently within it. Switching tools mid-campaign breaks trend comparisons.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimizing for the score instead of the underlying signals</strong> — The score is a proxy. Optimize GBP, reviews, citations, and local content. The score will follow.</li>
          <li><strong>No monthly check-in</strong> — Scores that aren't monitored regularly miss the early signs of competitor gains or algorithm updates. A 10-point drop caught in month 1 is a minor correction; a 30-point drop caught after 4 months requires a full recovery campaign.</li>
        </ul>

